00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:39.500
Here is a famous graph produced
by Benjamin bloom and

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:40.560
his students.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:42.910
So here on this axis is
student achievement.

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:54.550
So after a course is
over, students are

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:56.070
tested on the material.

00:00:56.070 --> 00:00:57.700
And here's their score.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:01.020
And this is the percentage
who attained each score.

00:01:01.020 --> 00:01:05.610
So here, they compared three
methods of teaching, but I'll

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:07.660
just compare two.

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:12.460
So one method is standard
one-group instruction, say

00:01:12.460 --> 00:01:15.440
one-to-30, or today,
maybe one-to-90.

00:01:21.672 --> 00:01:25.180
And here is the histogram, the
distribution of students'

00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:28.400
scores, nicely spread out.

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:30.050
Now, by itself, it
doesn't say much.

00:01:30.050 --> 00:01:34.890
But what's really interesting is
the distribution base after

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:38.510
the same amount of teaching, but
done in a tutorial form,

00:01:38.510 --> 00:01:40.260
with one-to-one or
maybe one-to-two.

00:01:48.244 --> 00:01:51.340
You can put some quantitative
figures on this

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:53.690
from Bloom's results.

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:54.830
The average--

00:01:54.830 --> 00:02:06.810
so this is one-to-one
tutoring, one-to-30.

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:13.830
The average tutorial student is
two sigmas better than the

00:02:13.830 --> 00:02:15.020
group students.

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:17.830
In other words, the average
tutorial student is at the

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:22.840
98th percentile of the ordinary
teaching group.

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:26.610
So the question is--

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:31.870
the natural question is, how can
we make group instruction

00:02:31.870 --> 00:02:35.260
as effective as tutorial
instruction?

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:40.310
As Benjamin Bloom says, he says,
finding such methods

00:02:40.310 --> 00:02:42.680
would be an educational
contribution of

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:44.190
the greatest magnitude.

00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:46.230
Because, for example,
it would change our

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:48.340
notions about human potential.

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:51.540
We'd actually realize, oh,
actually, there's not that

00:02:51.540 --> 00:02:54.530
much innate in what
people can do.

00:02:54.530 --> 00:02:57.080
Most of it is how well they've
learned, how well

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:58.750
they've been taught.

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:01.590
So the great question--

00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:04.170
and it's the title of Bloom's
paper-- is the search for

00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:06.980
methods of group instruction
as effective

00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:09.540
as one-to-one tutoring.

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:13.320
To that end, let's think about
the following question, which

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:17.220
is, what makes tutoring
so effective?

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:20.460
So I'm going to ask you that,
to consider that question in

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:24.140
groups of two and three,
whatever's sort of convenient

00:03:24.140 --> 00:03:25.960
in your region of the room.

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:28.990
So, what makes tutoring
so effective?

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:32.320
After you discuss, we'll take
reasons, put them on the

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:36.700
board, and then I'll show you
methods of group instruction

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:39.770
that may not quite get us all
the way to tutoring, but that

00:03:39.770 --> 00:03:42.790
answer many of the good
characteristics of tutoring

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:45.940
and bring them into
group instruction.

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:48.910
OK, so please find one
or two neighbors.

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:50.980
Introduce yourselves.

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:51.540
You never know.

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:54.400
You might find a teaching
colleague.

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:58.450
And think about what makes
tutoring so effective.

00:03:58.450 --> 00:04:02.670
OK, so take 30 seconds
and collect

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:03.920
your thoughts together.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:12.020
OK, who would like to suggest
something that your group

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:12.360
thought of?

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:14.720
You don't necessarily have to
believe it, just something you

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:17.740
discussed and think
we should share.

00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:22.570
Yes?

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:23.430
Could you tell me your name?

00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:24.140
AUDIENCE: Elena.

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:24.485
PROFESSOR: Elena.

00:04:24.485 --> 00:04:26.990
AUDIENCE: For one-on-one
tutoring, I imagine there's

00:04:26.990 --> 00:04:31.554
less time for misconceptions
to get

00:04:31.554 --> 00:04:33.030
ingrained in your brain.

00:04:33.030 --> 00:04:35.100
PROFESSOR: OK, you can nip
misconceptions in the bud.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:48.820
Whereas in, for example, group
instruction, you may not even

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:50.750
know the students have
a misconception

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:53.090
until the final exam.

00:04:53.090 --> 00:04:55.510
Then what do you do?

00:04:55.510 --> 00:04:57.320
OK, let's see.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:04:58.766
This group, could you
tell me your name?

00:04:58.766 --> 00:04:59.580
AUDIENCE: So we thought--

00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:00.840
PROFESSOR: Could you
tell me your name?

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:01.302
AUDIENCE: Eric.

00:05:01.302 --> 00:05:02.688
PROFESSOR: Eric.

00:05:02.688 --> 00:05:05.030
AUDIENCE: We thought in a group,
there's probably a lot

00:05:05.030 --> 00:05:08.774
of just dissemination
of information.

00:05:08.774 --> 00:05:11.259
And in one-on-one tutoring, it's
probably not one person

00:05:11.259 --> 00:05:13.605
just telling person two
a bunch of stuff.

00:05:13.605 --> 00:05:16.440
It's going through
exam problems.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:17.010
PROFESSOR: Right, OK.

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:20.640
So the contrast in this is
what does the teaching

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:21.520
situation look like?

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:25.430
In a typical lecture, someone
may just talk at you for 50

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:28.970
minutes, whereas it's hard to
imagine a one-on-one tutorial

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:31.960
situation where you walk in for
your tutorial, and they

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:33.820
just talk at you
for 50 minutes.

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:37.400
That would seem so odd and so
counter to all conventions of

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:38.650
human discussion.

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:42.800
It would take a really, really
disciplined and well-trained

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:44.840
person to sit still for 50
minutes for that kind of

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:49.880
treatment, so not initially a
good kind of training either.

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:55.140
OK, so I'll say you cannot
yammer at the audience for 50

00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:56.390
minutes straight.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:09.830
Yes, can you tell
me your name?

00:06:09.830 --> 00:06:10.370
AUDIENCE: Sorry?

00:06:10.370 --> 00:06:11.570
PROFESSOR: Could you
tell me your name?

00:06:11.570 --> 00:06:12.120
AUDIENCE: I'm Whitney.

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:12.660
PROFESSOR: Whitney

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:16.580
AUDIENCE: I think it follows
from this discussion that

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:24.420
arises between two people that
the student experiences

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:27.360
validation of what they've
understood, and it helps build

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:28.360
their confidence.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.830
PROFESSOR: OK, because they're
talking in a small group, so

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:33.050
they can get validation
in a safe setting.

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:34.640
Is that?

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:37.440
OK, so it's safe.

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:43.890
It's a safe setting for raising
ideas maybe that

00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:45.140
you're not sure about.

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:55.280
OK, there was one more.

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:56.330
Yeah, can you tell
me your name?

00:06:56.330 --> 00:06:56.870
AUDIENCE: Martin.

00:06:56.870 --> 00:06:57.670
PROFESSOR: Martin.

00:06:57.670 --> 00:06:58.315
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:58.315 --> 00:07:01.030
With tutoring, it's much easier
to identify exactly

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:04.930
what the student has trouble
understanding, and then tailor

00:07:04.930 --> 00:07:07.026
the teaching according
to that.

00:07:07.026 --> 00:07:09.810
PROFESSOR: OK, so you can tailor
the teaching according

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:11.230
to what you find out.

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:15.920
So sort of like the new
electronic SATs.

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.410
According to what you don't
know or do know, in each

00:07:18.410 --> 00:07:20.930
question, they give you
questions based on your

00:07:20.930 --> 00:07:23.600
previous answers at the right
level of difficulty.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:24.850
So you can tailor.

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:37.550
Yeah, can you tell
me your name?

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:37.890
AUDIENCE: Azrael.

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:39.462
PROFESSOR: Azrael, yeah.

00:07:39.462 --> 00:07:42.360
AUDIENCE: I think related to
this, it's very valuable to be

